      <font color="#ff0033"><b>Some Statistics: (From the book Startup: The Complete Handbook for Launching a Company for Less&#160;&#160;)</b></font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>FOR THE FIRST TWO YEARS:</b>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Over 530,000 new businesses are created each month in the U.S.
      </li>
      <li>
        On average, entrepreneurs make $30,000&#8211;$40,000 in the first few years&#8212;just enough to survive.
      </li>
      <li>
        Typically in the first year, you&#8217;re on your own. Only 21% of new businesses hire someone else in the first year - which means that you&#8217;re now in charge of sales, business development, new product development, marketing, advertising, accounting, administrative duties.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <b>RATIONAL AND IRRATIONAL RISK FACTORS FOR STARTUPS:</b>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        According to the SBA, over 50% of small businesses fail in the first five years.
      </li>
    </ul>
